            "question_text": "Hence, solve the simultaneous equations \\(x + 2y = 5\\) and \\(x^2 - xy = 2\\).",
            "solution_text": "From \\(x + 2y = 5\\), we have \\(2y = 5 - x\\), so \\(y = \\frac{5-x}{2}\\).\nSubstituting this into \\(x^2 - xy = 2\\):\n\\(x^2 - x(\\frac{5-x}{2}) = 2\\)\n\\(2x^2 - x(5-x) = 4\\)\n\\(2x^2 - 5x + x^2 = 4\\)\n\\(3x^2 - 5x - 4 = 0\\)\n\\((3x + 1)(x - 4) = 0\\)\nSo \\(x = -\\frac{1}{3}\\) or \\(x = 4\\).\n\nWhen \\(x = -\\frac{1}{3}\\):\n\\(2y = 5 - (-\\frac{1}{3}) = 5 + \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{16}{3}\\)\n\\(y = \\frac{16}{6} = \\frac{8}{3}\\)\nWhen \\(x = 4\\):\n\\(2y = 5 - 4 = 1\\)\n\\(y = \\frac{1}{2}\\)\n\nTherefore, the solutions are \\(x = -\\frac{1}{3}\\), \\(y = \\frac{8}{3}\\) and \\(x = 4\\), \\(y = \\frac{1}{2}\\)."
